{{Update|''CEO and financial data''|inaccurate=yes|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox company |name = Iron Ore Company of Canada |logo = [[Image:Iron Ore Company Canada.png|center|200px]] |type = [[Subsidiary company]] |slogan = |foundation = (1949) [[Wilmington, Delaware]], United States |location = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada |key_people = Clayton Walker , [[President (corporate title)|President]] |revenue = {{profit}}$2.471 Billion [[US dollar|US]] (2011) |industry = Mining |num_employees = 1,900 (2005) |products = Iron ore |homepage = {{URL|www.ironore.ca}} |}}
'''Iron Ore Company of Canada''' (often abbreviated to '''IOC''') ({{lang-fr|Compagnie Minière IOC}}) is a [[Canada|Canadian]]-based producer of [[iron ore]]. The company was founded in 1949 from a partnership of Canadian and American [[M.A. Hanna Company]].<ref>Hollinger, M.A. Hanna, Labrador Mining, National Republic, Armco, Youngston and Wheeling-Pittsburg</ref> It is now owned by a new consortium,<ref>Mitsubishi Corp., Rio Tinto Limited, LIORIF and IOC Ore Sales Company</ref> including the [[Mitsubishi]] and [[Rio Tinto Group|Rio Tinto]] corporations. Rio Tinto is the majority shareholder in the venture, with 58.7% of the joint stock as of October 2013.<ref>[http://business.financialpost.com/2013/10/15/rio-tinto-to-complete-iron-ore-company-of-canada-expansion-by-mid-2014/ FP: "Rio Tinto to complete Iron Ore Company of Canada expansion by mid-2014" 15 Oct 2013]</ref> Mitsubishi controlled 26.2% of the investment as of March 2013.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/dented-by-aluminum-rio-tinto-aims-to-unload-iron-ore-co/article9201005/ G+M: "Dented by aluminum, Rio Tinto aims to unload Iron Ore Co" 1 Mar 2013]</ref>
Based in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], IOC currently has mining and concentrator operations in [[Labrador City]], and operates the [[Quebec North Shore and Labrador Railway]] to ship ore concentrate from the mines, such as [[Wabush]], to the port of [[Sept-Îles, Quebec|Sept-Îles]], [[Quebec]].
During 1977 to 1983, the president of the company was [[Brian Mulroney]], who later served as [[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] from 1984 to 1993.
