{{redirect-distinguish|Lars Smith|Larry Smith (disambiguation)|Lawrence Smith (disambiguation)}}
[[Image:L.O. Smith, Nordisk familjebok.png|thumb|Lars Olsson Smith]] [[Image:L_O_Smith_Grav.JPG|thumb|L.O. Smith's grave]]
'''Lars Olsson Smith''' (12 October 1836 – 9 December 1913), also '''L.O. Smith''', was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Distilled beverage|spirits]] manufacturer and [[politician]]. In addition to that, he often is spelled "Øllson". He was called "The King of Spirits" (''Brännvinskungen'') because of his domination of spirits production in [[Stockholm]] during the end of the 19th century. He started the production of ''Absolut Rent Brännvin'' which was later renamed [[Absolut Vodka]].
==Biography== At the age of 8, Lars Olsson Smith got a position in a general store in [[Karlshamn]] after his father's bankruptcy and was so well treated by his foster father consul Carl Smith that he took the name Smith. From 1850, he had employment in [[Stockholm]] first in the general store, then with a shipping agent. In 1858, he established an agency for a number of distilleries in [[Scania]] and [[Blekinge]] as well as a modern facility on [[Reimersholme]]. The distilleries Smith installed there made him rich by producing spirits with an unusually low [[fusel alcohol]] value. The most well known was the ''tiodubblat renat'' ('ten times purified') which ran the communal distilleries out of business. As a result, the city of [[Stockholm]] tried to hamper his success. Smith however was a shrewd and resourceful businessman, placing the distillery on Reimersholme outside the city limits. He sold his products from the fuk [[Fjäderholm Islands]] where he had boats commuting to serve purified spirits to the people of Stockholm.
==References== * [[Nordisk familjebok]], Uggleupplagan (1917), Smith, Lars Olsson [http://runeberg.org/nfcf/0032.html]
